%N A327131 Cells visited by knight moves on a spirally numbered infinite hexagonal board, moving to the lowest unvisited cell at each step.
%C A327131 The infinite hexagonal board is numbered spirally as:
%C A327131 .
%C A327131       17--18--19...
%C A327131      /
%C A327131     16   6---7---8
%C A327131    /    /         \
%C A327131   15   5   1---2   9
%C A327131    \    \     /   /
%C A327131     14   4---3  10
%C A327131      \          /
%C A327131       13--12--11
%C A327131 .
%C A327131 In Glinski's hexagonal chess, a knight (N) can move to these (o) cells:
%C A327131 .
%C A327131       . . . . .
%C A327131      . . o o . .
%C A327131     . o . . . o .
%C A327131    . o . . . . o .
%C A327131   . . . . N . . . .
%C A327131    . o . . . . o .
%C A327131     . o . . . o .
%C A327131      . . o o . .
%C A327131       . . . . .
%C A327131 .
%C A327131 This sequence is finite and ends at a(83966) = 72085 when the knight is "trapped".
